If you're looking for a girl who knows how to travel…here I am! 😂⁣
⁣
Flying has become a necessary part of my life as a photographer… sooo I’ve learned some incredible HACKS to make traveling more fun. (Because who wants to be miserable for 10hrs straight? Not this girl).⁣
⁣
✨Here are my top 4 airport survival hacks…⁣
⁣
1. Bring noise canceling headphones. I went from never sleeping on flights to knocking out for complete 10hr flights with this hack. They don’t need to be fancy, just something to cut the edge off of that loud airplane engine humming and baby screaming will do the trick.😉⁣
⁣
2. Don’t be afraid to ask questions! You never know if your flight has a lot of open seats that they’ll upgrade you to (just cuz)! Most people are too afraid to ask…so don’t be afraid to be kind and brave! It’s always worth a shot!.🙌⁣
⁣
3. Bring gum. There are multiple reasons for gum. It helps your ears adjust to the air pressure at takeoff, it keeps your breath from getting bad, it gives you something to do, and it stops you from buying those RIDICULOUSLY overpriced airline snacks.⁣
⁣
4. Make use of those nifty massage chairs while waiting on your layover! I feel so much better better when sitting in one of those bad boys after being cramped in a uncomfortable tiny airplane seat for hours.⁣
⁣
There are a MILLION other little tips, but those are my favorites!⁣
⁣
🧐What’s your best airport hack? Aisle or window seat? Bring a toothbrush? pack a snack?⁣

Let's talk about lighting. 💡

When indoors, we like to shoot by windows to take advantage of the light, as well as open all the curtains to bring as much light as possible into a room.

Here in Hawaii, many of our weddings are outdoors, which is great for light! When creating your timeline, try and avoid 11:30-12:30 if possible as this is when the sun is directly above and shadows are not the best to work with. The best times for good light are mornings, afternoon, and our favorite sunset!

-Rings
-Jewelry

I had a couple of wedding inquiry consultation calls this week, and I love hearing how each couple met! 

For those of you who don't know Rui and I met at work, he was the checker, and I was the bagger at the grocery store. He asked me out by saying, "I'll see you tomorrow?" and I replied,"I'm off tomorrow." Then, an hour later, he said it again, and I said, "But I'm off tomorrow." Then he did it again 20 mins later, and at this point, I was like,"I just told you I'm off tomorrow, remember?" Then he said,"I know, but we could go out on a date." I said yes, and we went ice skating for our first date! 

How did you meet your significant other?

Rui and I have been photographing people in love for over 10 years. You can usually find us barefooted at the beach, reading a good book, or being goofy and hanging out with our family. Of course, when we are not doing any of that, we are third-wheeling with couples, camera in hand. 

One of the biggest benefits we love about being a husband and wife team is that together, we can best serve our couples. Rui has his own set of strengths that are different than mine, and I have a another set of strengths that are different from his. Here is a great example that we like to use in describing this scenario. You know when you've been together with someone for a long time and you can just tell by the expression on their face or body language what that other person is thinking of feeling? That is what it is like for us when we are working together. I can look over at Rui and know exactly what angle he is getting, and what shot I need to get. Or he can look at me and just with one glance let me know if I'm in his shot or need to capture a different moment happening elsewhere. It's like we're reading each other minds...kinda :D Our clients love the consistency and communication that comes from always having the same two shooters.
